        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See letters to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3589.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Daniel Oliver</ref>, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2913.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">11 September [1860]</ref> and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2917.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">15 [September 1860]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">This was opposed to CD’s view that only nitrogenous matter caused the inflection of the leaves.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The term ‘endosmose’ was coined by René Joachim <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1434.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Henri Dutrochet</ref>. He established that ‘when two liquids of different densities or of different chemical natures are separated by a membranous partition, two currents are established across this partition, going in opposite directions, and unequal in force’. Dutrochet called the movement of fluid into organic tissue under these conditions ‘endosmose’. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Dutrochet 1828</ref>, p. 1.</note>
